  "duration": 244.75500460799998,
  "text": " What is organizational learning? It is the process of detecting and correcting errors in organizations. There are two different types of organizational learning. 1. Single loop learning Is error correction by following rules and operating norms when solving a problem? 1. Scan the environment 2. Compare to operating norms 3. Appropriate action Example the thermostat It only operates by following these rules It detects that the specific room is warm, so it turns down the temperature, or it detects that the room is too cold, so it turns up the temperature. But what if you were to question the operating norms Now it is double loop learning One scan the environment two compare to operating norms two a question operating norms and three appropriate action. Two a questioning the operating norms. Two double loop learning. Use error correction by changing and critically questioning the rules and operating norms when solving problems. This learning involves more thinking outside the box. Creativity is a must when questioning and thinking outside the operating norms. Double loop learning allows us to question which situation is the best to reach our end goal Let go back to the thermostat example What if it was able to question and critically think about why that temperature is the best for the situation? This is called double loop learning. Now the thermostat is comparing the operating norms to see which temperature is the best for the room. Now, we are using critically questioning, thinking, and problem solving in the organization.",
